The study concludes that various factors contribute to women’s perception of the marital event as negative where marriage is without a doubt the most popular means of women to secure economic independence and insurable status. Due to the woman’s dependence on the husband it was found that in cases if divorce one of the major issues in court will be division of “joint property.” (most property acquired by the male spouse during the marriage). In 2013 the chief justice ruled in the case of Mara VS Mara that the concept of equal shared property does not apply to single matrimonial property cases since an individual would have acquired the property alone during a life time and was therefore entitled to sole ownership [40] however this definition failed to consider the property that was jointly purchased during marriage. This continued to place women at risk of losing their home on divorce. The Law reforms bill 2019 seeks to introduce a share to marriage property in the event of divorce [41]
5.1 Marital Property The Law Reform (Marital Property Rights) Bill, 2018 (“the Bill”) now seeks to change the law of mariage property in Kenya by allowing ultility of labour, contributions, as well as the financial contributions of the couple to be considered when dividing marital property (property acquired during marriage) [42] The bill was published in copy in the Kenya gazette on September, 2018 and scheduled
